gions, in departments small and large,\xe2\x80\x99 Rita Gardner, director of the Royal Geographical Society, said. Michael Hyland, professor of health psychology at the University of Plymouth, said there was a question mark over the higher education establishment\xe2\x80\x99s assumption that teaching and research are inex- tricably linked. \xe2\x80\x98Research-active staff argue that they are more up-to-date. But this can be achieved through scholarship rather than active research . . . and the content of most undergraduate courses is at least a few years old,\xe2\x80\x99 he said. The THES\xe2\x80\x99s lead editorial pointed out that the Government\xe2\x80\x99s position rests on the fact that no clear evidence of a link between teaching and research has been produced.\xe2\x80\x9d\nDo lecturers need to research? The Times \xe2\x80\x93 London. September 9, 2003\nDownloaded from by guest on April 20, 2017\nARTICLES 1237\nNoted by JFL, MD\nBullying Among Young Adolescents: The Strong, the Weak, and the Troubled\nJaana Juvonen, Sandra Graham and Mark A. Schuster Pediatrics 2003;112;1231\n Updated Information & Services\nReferences\nCitations\nSubspecialty Collections\nPermissions & Licensing\nReprints\nincluding high resolution figures, can be found at:\n/content/112/6/1231.full.html\nThis article cites 18 articles, 2 of which can be accessed free at:\n/content/112/6/1231.full.html#ref-list-1\nThis article has been cited by 60 HighWire-hosted articles:\n/content/112/6/1231.full.html#related-urls\nThis article, along with others on similar topics, appears in the following collection(s):\nAdministration/Practice Management /cgi/collection/administration:practice_management_sub\nInformation about reproducing this article in parts (figures, tables) or in its entirety can be found online at: /site/misc/Permissions.xhtml\nInformation about ordering reprints can be found online:\n/site/misc/reprints.xhtml\n PEDIATRICS is the official journal of the American Academy of Pediatric