ter in high school compared to primary schools, greater when facilitators were other than the teachers (researchers, counselors or software). The programs had very small effects on empathy (g = .05, 95% CI: .07\xe2\x80\x93.17). Victimization significantly predicts internalizing problems over time (r = .18, 95% CI = .12\xe2\x80\x93.24) and, on the other hand, internalizing problems significantly predict victimization over time (r = .08, 95% CI .01\xe2\x80\x93.16), although the effect size was very small for the latter.\nVictimization significantly predicts externalizing problems over time (r = .14, 95% CI: .09\xe2\x80\x93.19) and, on the other hand, externalizing problems significantly predict victimization over time (r = .13, 95% CI: .04\xe2\x80\x93.21). Victimization was positively related to low socioeconomic status (OR = 1.52, 95% CI: 1.36\xe2\x80\x931.71) and negatively related to high socioeconomic status (OR = .73, 95% CI: .63\xe2\x80\x93.86). Similar results were found for perpetration and socioeconomic status (low\xe2\x80\x94OR =1.14, 95% CI: 1.02\xe2\x80\x931.27 and high\xe2\x80\x94OR = .89, 95% CI: .83\xe2\x80\x93.95). Being a bully-victim was only positively related to low socioeconomic status (OR = 1.71, 95% CI: 1.22\xe2\x80\x932.39). Some of these associations become much weaker when adjusted for publication bias.\nPerpetration was an important predictor of violence later in life (adjusted OR = 2.04; 95% CI: 1.69\xe2\x80\x932.45). The effect size was negatively related to the age of perpetration assessment, the age of outcome assessment and the length of follow-ups (the effects of perpetration seem to decrease with time but early exposure predicts higher risk). Victimization was also a predictor of later violence, although with smaller effect size (adjusted OR = 1.42; 95% CI: 1.25\xe2\x80\x931.62) and no moderators were significant.\nBullying perpetrators are at higher risk for drug use (OR = 2.22, 95% CI: 1.60\xe2\x80\x933.07) although much variation i