e ARB\xe2\x88\x92\n6\nTable 3. Bivariate Correlations of Variables in Logistic Regressions\nVariable\nVariable 123456\nof entering college students. Overall, findings validated prior studies indicating that women were at greater risk for SRT, but provided additional information about the incre- mental increase in risk women have when they engage in drinking sufficient to produce blackouts. Compared to men with no recent blackouts, women with recent blackouts were three to five times more likely to engage in SRT while drinking on all indices (unsafe, unplanned, and regretted), whereas men with a history of blackouts, and women with no blackouts, were only moderately at risk (all OR < 1.75). However, this risk taking for women with recent blackouts occurred in the context of lower levels of alcohol use and greater expectancies of dangerousness from alcohol. Consistent with prior studies (White et al., 2002), women with recent blackouts reported significantly less overall alcohol involvement and fewer aggregate alcohol-related problems than men reporting blackouts. Similarly, within the blackout conditions, no differences were found for risky drinking styles like binge consumption, pregaming, or drinking-game participation. Overall, results provide compelling evidence that blackout incidence increases the risk for SRT in women who drink.\nOne reason for investigating alcohol-related blackouts and gender in relation to SRT is the increasing concern over college student sexual health issues. Adolescents and college students represent nearly one-fourth of the new cases of STDs each year in the United States (Scholly, Katz, Gascoigne, & Holck, 2005). Results from this study\nSEX AND DRUGS AND STARTING SCHOOL\n         Gendera\nBlackout incidenceb Overall alcohol use Unplanned sexb Unsafe sexb Regretted sexb\n\xe2\x80\x94\n\xe2\x88\x92.06 \xe2\x80\x94 \xe2\x88\x92.30** .39** \xe2\x88\x92.05 .34** \xe2\x88\x92.01 .24** \xe2\x88\x92.05 .27**\n\xe2\x80\x94\n.50** \xe2\x80\x94\