y comparisons; OR = odds ratio based on reference group; CI = confidence intervals for odds ratios. **p < .001.\nindex. Male ARB\xe2\x88\x92 group used as reference group for ARB by gender\n7\nindicated that nearly 40% of the sample had engaged in unsafe or unplanned sexual activity in the past three months while drinking. These risky sexual behaviors increase the likelihood of an individual failing to use protection (e.g. condom use), which contributes to negative consequences such as unplanned pregnancy and STDs. An increase in number of sexual partners from unplanned sexual activity and unsafe practices are both known to increase the prob- ability of human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) exposure (Fromme et al., 1999). Unwanted or unplanned pregnancies are potentially life-changing consequences that can impact a student\xe2\x80\x99s academic success. As such, women are dispropor- tionally experiencing negative burdens due to unplanned pregnancies.\nIn addition to the sexual health concerns, understanding alcohol-related blackouts and SRT in this population is of importance due to the challenges associated with being young adults. Often referred to as transitional youth, as they have left adolescence but have yet to grasp the responsibilities of adulthood (Arnett, 2000; Hicks & Heastie, 2008), the uncertainty and instability in the lives of young adults makes this population a concern of its own (Arnett, 2007). Issues of concern for these transitional youth include renegotiating family relationships and sup- port, forming new peer relationships, (Hicks & Heastie, 2008), coping with loss of high school friends (Cleary, Walter, & Jackson, 2011), psychological health issues, identity exploration, exploration of romantic relationships, and increases in experimentation (Arnett, 2000). Several types of risky behaviors peak during ages 18 to 25, includ- ing unprotected sex, substance use, and risky driving beha- viors (Arnett, 2000). These risky behaviors can be understood through an identity exploration lens as young people desire to have diverse experiences before obtaining the responsibilities and commitments that come with an adult life. The transition out of their childhood home is the first opportunity many of these young adults have to indi- viduate and explore their newfound freedoms (Hicks & Heastie, 2008), giving rise to a concern for possible increased risky behaviors. Increased autonomy and a lack of monitoring by parents allow young adults to pursue their desire for new experiences (i.e., risky behaviors) more freely. Research has shown that during the transition from high school to college there are increases in both number of sexual partners and alcohol use (Fromme et al., 2008). Decreased supervision, increased freedom, and increased availability for both sexual partners and alcohol use were found to be factors contributing to the risky behaviors for young adults (Fromme et al., 2008).\nLimitations and Future Directions\nAlthough the findings of this study add to the existing literature on blackouts and SRT in college students, it is not without limitations. The current sample utilized data from a relatively understudied, high-risk group of students (i.e., entering freshmen), examined SRT during an important\ndevelopmental transition (precollege), and found modest group differences on alcohol consumption, expectancies, and problem indices, including specific SRT behaviors. Though representative of the larger student body at our study site, the sample was collected at a single site at a private university, which limits the generalizability of the results. In particular, this site has a high percentage of freshmen who would be residing on campus, and it is unclear if the same predictors would emerge if this study was conducted at a location with more commuter students who planned to reside at home. In a similar vein, we did not assess parental or participant socioeconomic status (SES) in this study, and we acknowledge that a private university in the San Francisco area may draw students who are better off financially relative to other institutions. Both of these factors could influence access to alcohol and/or social norms regarding use and sexual activity, precollege as well as upon matriculation. Future research would benefit from a multisite, multicohort, multiyear design to address cohort effect, determine behavioral changes over time, and increase generalizability across colleges in the United States.\nAnother potential limitation was the cross-sectional nat- ure of the data collected and the manner with which black- outs, SRT behaviors, and alcohol use were measured. This study asked separate items that evaluated alcohol consump- tion and problems during the transition from high school to college, but did not include items that would allow for event-level associations between alcohol use, blackout inci- dence, and SRT. Future research may want to consider utilizing other measures, such as a modified timeline fol- low-back interview (Sobell & Sobell, 1992), and/or data collection approaches (e.g., diary studies) to examine the intersection of these consequences within discrete drinking events. Another direction may be to examine how SRT and blackout relate to specific drinking events which involve risky styles of drinking and which have a higher probability of blackout. Prior research has identified risk factors for blackout like use of hard alcohol, chugging drinks, and restricting food on drinking days (Lee et al., 2009). Future studies should consider collecting event-level data that cap- tures risky drinking practices with these characteristics, like pregaming or drunkorexia (i.e., limiting food intake before alcohol consumption; Barry & Piazza-Gardner, 2012). In addition, this study focused on three SRT behaviors identi- fied in prior studies (unsafe, unplanned, and regretted) but did not assess other characteristics of sexuality that may differ by gender-blackout group. Future research should consider including measures that allow for a more intensive study of sexual history and recent sexual experiences. For example, alcohol use has been shown to be associated with casual sexual relationships with higher levels of SRT, like hookups, one-night stands, and friends with benefits (Grello et al., 2006; Owen & Fincham, 2011a, 2011b). Future studies may want to include measures to assess these dimen- sions as well, to provide a broader view of how blackouts and gender contribute to participation in these kinds of sexual arrangements.\n8\nHAAS, BARTHEL, AND TAYLOR\nImplications and Final Remarks\nOverall, findings from this study provide direct implica- tions for future research, prevention, and intervention efforts. This study adds to the growing literature implicating consequences associated with escalations in overall risk taking, as well as drinking, during the precollege transition. Results highlight that SRT while drinking occurs at rela- tively high base rates during this time frame, and that black- outs and engagement in multiple kinds of SRT, including unwanted, unsafe, and regretted acts, are related through alcohol use.\nFindings also emphasize that women are at greater risk, despite drinking less. As such, prevention efforts should emphasize consequences associated with alcohol use with gender differences in mind and emphasize the intersectionality between problems. Though this kind of psychoeducation occurs in many existing campus pre- vention programs through commercially available online programming, additional materials may enhance under- standing and/or integration of this information into women\xe2\x80\x99s drinking and the role of alcohol in their sexual decision making. For example, campuses may want to consider creating posters or similar media with informa- tion about gender differences in alcohol metabolism, which could be posted in common areas on campus throughout the year. Comparable media could be intro- duced to highlight the problem of blackout, consent, and sexual practices engaged in while under the influence. Such media could provide education around different BACs and level of alcohol consumption for blackouts to occur in men and women, as well as dose-dependent information about when decision making and consent may be impaired. Similar campaigns have been used in conjunction with alcohol-related social norms interven- tions with some success (Glider, Midyett, Mills-Novoa, Johannessen, & Collins, 2001). Though by no means a solution, media like this are low cost and, if developed in a manner that appeals to students, may help mitigate risk on campus. While prevention efforts geared toward college entry are important, given the diverse concerns that young adults transitioning out of high school face, intervention programs designed for high school students during their final semester should be considered, given the numerous opportunities this population has for risky behaviors. Such a program may help reduce risk of increased engagement during the transitional period. While many universities offer programs for incoming freshmen, programs targeting students while they are still in high school and during their transition to college may be a more effective approach (Fromme et al., 2008). Applying the aforementioned prevention strategies at school assemblies or requiring small group format infor- mation sessions on blackouts and SRT may be a way to help educate transitional youth.\nReferences\nSEX AND DRUGS AND STARTING SCHOOL\nAbbey, A., Ross, L. T., McDuffie, D., & McAuslan, P. (1996). Alcohol and dating risk factors for sexual assault among college women. Psychology of Women Quarterly, 20, 147\xe2\x80\x93169. doi:10.1111/j.1471- 6402.1996.tb00669.x\nAbbey, A., Saenz, C., & Buck, P. O. (2005). The cumulative effects of acute alcohol consumption, individual differences, and situational perceptions on sexual decision making. Journal of Studies on Alcohol, 66(1), 82\xe2\x80